# Approach
Approach is using Basic maths in which we separate the digits. Then used vector to store all the digits. The elements or digits stored in vector are in the opposite form like 10 so in vector it will not be saved as 1,0 but 0,1. Now if the vector size is even then even indices elements must be negative. And if vector size is odd then odd indices digits or elements will be negative.

**Note: That digits will be store in opposite order.**

*For eg-1:* 10 => 0,1 => indices 0,2,4.... so on will be negative => So it becomes -0,1 => (-0)+(+1) = 1

*For eg-2:* 521 => 1,2,5 (opposite form of digits in vector) => The vector size is odd => indices 1,3,5.... so on will be negative => So it becomes (+1)+(-2)+(+5) = 1-2+5 = -1+5 = 4

At the end of for loop in each iteration we are updating sum of elements and then returning it.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
As loops are used (NOT NESTED) 
1. One loop for separting and putting digits in vector using .push_back() => O(n)
2. Second loop for iteration through vector simultaneously checking the size of vector for even or odd and respectively converting even or odd indices to negative. => O(n)

Finally updating the sum of elements in vector for each iteration.

So time complexity is O(n+n) = O(2n) => O(n)

- Space complexity:
As we are using a vector to store the digits or elements and finding sum so same complexity is O(n).

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int alternateDigitSum(int n) {
        vector<int> vec;
        while(n!=0){
            int x=n%10;
            vec.push_back(x);
            n=n/10;
        }
        int sum=0;
        for(int i=0;i<vec.size();i++){
            if((vec.size())%2==0){
                if(i%2==0){
                    vec[i]=-vec[i];
                }
            }
            else if((vec.size())%2!=0){
                if(i%2!=0){
                    vec[i]=-vec[i];
                }
            }
            sum+=vec[i];
        }
        return sum;
    }
};
```

