# Intuition
###### What is *Most Significant Digit*?
According to the site [Datacademia](https://datacadamia.com/data/type/number/significant#:~:text=Definition%20Most%20The%20most%20significant%20digit%20is%20the,least%20significant%20digit%20is%20the%20right-most%20known%20digit.) the formal definition of **Most Significant Digit** is:
> The ***most significant digit** is the **left-most nonzero digit** 
> Where as The least significant digit is the right-most known digit.

Thus :

- `n=25` :  (+2) + (-5)  = -3
- `n=521` : (+5) + (-2) + (+1) = 4
- `n=1234` : (+1) + (-2) + (+3) + (-4) = -2
- `n=886996` : (+8) + (-8) + (+6) + (-9) + (+9) + (-6) = 0

# Approach
- Fetch the count of the number of Digits in the given number `n`
- We will use the count as indexing for manipulating the power of $$-1$$ to control the sign of the digits
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/ffcc178d-f992-44ca-aef3-47d4b0a0422c_1674409969.6540778.png)

- Here digit multiplied by (-1) raised to the power of the index gives the required corresponding sign. *Refer to the above image*
- ***By the Problem:*** The Most significant digit will always be multiplied by (-1) raised to the power 0 thus will always be **Positive**.


# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(m)$$ 
  *where **m** is the number of digits in `n`*

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int alternateDigitSum(int n) {
        int sum=0, n1=n, ctr=0;
        while(n1>0)
        {
            n1/=10;
            ctr++;
        }
        while(n>0)
        {
            int d = n%10;
            sum += d*Math.pow(-1, --ctr);
            // --ctr gives the index of each digit
            n=n/10;            
        }
        return sum;
    }
}
```
